User Management API

Project Highlights

Lightweight Minimal API built with ASP.NET Core (.NET 8)

Full CRUD functionality: create, read, update, delete users

Validation and error handling for robust API behavior

Middleware support for logging requests/responses and authentication

Auto-generated unique IDs for users

Perfect for learning modern backend practices or as a foundation for larger applications

Overview

The User Management API allows you to manage users efficiently with a clean, modern API design. It enforces validation, handles errors gracefully, and includes middleware for logging and security. Designed to be lightweight, easy to use, and extendable.

Features

CRUD Operations

Create users (POST)

Get all users (GET)

Get user by ID (GET)

Update user by ID (PUT)

Delete user by ID (DELETE)

Validation

Usernames cannot be empty

Age must be positive

Middleware

Request/response logging

Consistent JSON error messages

Optional token-based authentication

In-memory storage

Auto-generated unique IDs

Technologies Used

.NET 8

ASP.NET Core Minimal APIs

C#

Middleware (logging, error handling, authentication)

In-memory collections

Getting Started
Prerequisites

.NET 8 SDK

Visual Studio 2022 or VS Code

Run the API

Clone the repository:
git clone https://github.com/your-username/user-management-api.git

Navigate to the project directory:
cd user-management-api

Run the project:
dotnet run

API will be available at:
http://localhost:5062

API Endpoints
Method	Endpoint	Description
GET	/	Default endpoint to check API status
POST	/users/create	Create a new user
GET	/users/get	Retrieve all users
GET	/users/get/{id}	Retrieve a user by ID
PUT	/users/{id}	Update a user by ID
DELETE	/users/{id}	Delete a user by ID
Request Examples

Create a User
POST http://localhost:5062/users/create
Body:
{ "UserName": "Charlie", "Age": 28 }

Update a User
PUT http://localhost:5062/users/3
Body:
{ "UserName": "Bob Updated", "Age": 42 }

Get All Users
GET http://localhost:5062/users/get

Delete a User
DELETE http://localhost:5062/users/1

Middleware

Logging: Logs HTTP method, request path, and response status

Error Handling: Returns consistent JSON error messages for exceptions

Authentication (optional): Validates tokens for secure endpoints

